        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Requested sensitivity:
The predicted flux of IRAS 15099-5856 IRS1 at 1 mm (230 GHz) from the CLOUDY models is ~10 mJy (Fig. 2). This is consistent with the upper limit (30 mJy at 1.1mm) obtained 
by Koo et al. (2011) using the AzTEC bolometer array on the 10m telescope Atacama Submillimeter Telescope Experiment. Our Gemini-S Qa-band observation shows that the source 
is composed of two, centrally-brightened blobs of sizes &lt; 5" (Fig. 3). Assuming that the distribution of cold dust is similar to the MIR-emitting dust in Fig. 3, we get an 
average surface brightness of ~0.3 mJy/beam where the beam size is ~1" (configuration C34-2). The exact beam size will depend on how high the source is at the time of 
observation. At band 6, the continuum sensitivity for 1-min integration with a bandwidth of 7.5 GHz is 0.13 mJy/beam so that 1-hr of integration time with 6.5 GHz continuum 
bandwidth will yield a sensitivity of ~0.02 mJy/beam which would be enough for our purpose to get S/N &gt; ~15. The CASA simulation using the Gemini-S Qa-band image and 10 mJy 
of flux at 1 mm with 1-hr of integration time (Fig. 4 in Scientific Justification) shows that the ALMA continuum map will clearly reveal the distribution of cold dust. 

In case of line emission, we will be observing CO J=2-1 line emission (230.5380 GHz). We will use bandwidth of 938 MHz providing velocity coverage of 1200 km/s at 230 GHz. 
If we perform 1-hr integration at 230 GHz band with 0.49 MHz (0.64 km/s) spectral resolution, the resulting sensitivity is 2.2 mJy or 0.05 K for 1" beam. This is enough to 
detect optically thick CO clumps of &lt;= 1" size. If we detect CO emission, it will give a useful constraint on the molecular/dust content of the source and the mass-loss history 
of the source.


Imaging requirements:
The spatial scales of the structures in IRS1 range from 1" to ~5" according to Gemini-S/T-ReCS MIR images (Fig. 3). At 1 mm, where the emission from cold dust dominates, 
there could be structures of larger scale. ALMA configuration C34-2 should be ideal for our purpose, which will provide a beam size of ~1" and the maximum-observable angular 
scale of 11". The field of the 12-m array (27") is also enough to map the distribution of cold dust in IRS1. A simulation of ALMA observations using the Gemini-S/T-ReCS Qa-band 
continuum image of IRS1 as an input model image shows that the proposed ALMA observations will reconstruct the structures of IRS1 well (Fig. 4). Since the object is fairly 
compact, we do not require the ACA.


Correlator setup:
We will be doing dust continuum and CO J=2-1 line observations at band 6 (230 GHz). We assign three spectral windows for the continuum and one spectral window for the line 
observation. The first spectral window will be centered at the frequency of CO J=2-1 line in the USB of band 6. We choose an LSR velocity of -20 km/s which is the middle of 
two velocity components detected by the previous Mopra and ASTE CO J=2-1 observations. We select the bandwidth of 938 MHz with spectral resolution of 0.49 MHz (0.64 km/s). 
This is sufficient to study kinematics of the gas around the source. For continuum observations, following the suggestion in ALMA Cycle 2 Technical Handbook, we set one spectral 
window at 2 GHz below the CO J=2-1 line in the USB, and two other 2-GHz spectral windows in the LSB. 


Time constraints:
None.


User-defined' calibration:
Not necessary.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
