    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to make ALMA 1-mm observations of the infrared source IRAS 15099-5856 associated with a supernova remnant (SNR) detected by AKARI and Spitzer observations. IRAS 15099-5856 is the first infrared source that shows crystalline silicate features associated with an SNR. It is most likely that the crystalline silicates originated in a mass outflow from the progenitor of the SNR which was in a close binary system with the nearby (13") O star. Our CLOUDY modelling of the Spitzer IRS spectrum also supports this possibility. IRAS 15099-5856 will offer a unique opportunity to study the mass-loss and dust formation in a massive progenitor system, for which we have only little knowledge at present. Our recent Gemini-S [Ne II] and Qa-band imaging observations revealed that it has a complex mid-infrared dust-continuum structure over ~10" with superposed compact [Ne II]-bright peaks. ALMA continuum observations at 1 mm will show the distribution of cold dust and provide a constraint to estimate dust mass. Line observations will show molecular gases beyond dust, which will reveal the true nature and formation history of this intriguing object. </prp:abstract>
